The Data

My chosen dataset is taken from the eBird database. Ebird is an app/website run by the Cornell Lab of Ornithology, in which birdwatchers (from ornithologists to novices) can record bird observations. These observations are important contributions to wildlife biologists’ understanding of bird abundance, migration patterns, behaviors, etc. Ebird freely provides its data, and I was even able to request a custom dataset limited to a certain period of time (February 2019 to April 2020) and location (Charleston, South Carolina; this was arbitrary, but it’s my hometown). Within this dataset, each row is an individual observation made by a birder, and the variables contained in the columns are the birder’s responses to questions like bird common name and scientific name, observation count, date, locality, and number of observers. The columns also contain metadata like date the record was last edited and observer ID.

The Goals

I would like to examine differences between two time periods: March-April 2019 and March-April 2020. My general suspicion is that because the United States was in lockdown during this time period in 2020, there will be distinct differences between the two years. My goals are to report descriptive statistics on several different variables, wrangle the data as necessary and visualize results. Then, I will test two hypotheses relating to data about the birders themselves, rather than the birds. My thought process is that while the Cornell Lab of Ornithology and other authorities use eBird data to draw conclusions about bird abundance, migration patterns, etc, in those cases this user-contributed data is supplemented with biological research and expertise. Because I have nothing but the raw data, I would rather study the birders submitting the data.

Speaking of the ISS, I next want to take a look at the types of birding activity. The data contains a column called PROTOCOL.TYPE that has a handful of values, like “Stationary”, “Traveling”, and “International Shorebird Survey (ISS)”. According to the metadata file eBird included when they sent me the dataset, these indicate the type of activity the birder was participating in at the time of the observation. As stated before, the ISS is a bird count event, as are a couple of the other possible values in this variable. There is also “Banding”, which accounts for a fairly small amount of the observations since only trained professionals can band birds. I’m particularly interested in the “Traveling” option, which includes observations made as the birder walked, biked, or otherwise traversed some distance; and the “Stationary” option, which includes backyard bird watching or sitting at a park. I wondered if the proportion of “Stationary” observations rose in 2020, so I completed the following visualizations and simple analyses:

For my actual hypotheses, I want to look at birder group sizes. The numeric variable NUMBER.OBSERVERS indicates how many people were in the group that made the recorded observation. First, I want to get a sense of the numbers. This variable does contain NAs, and I decided the best idea was to remove them. Since I’m interested in whether or not birders were birding in groups, replacing NAs with 0 or 1 (to indicate at least one person was in this group) would artificially affect the analysis. I got the means of the number of observers during March-April in 2019 and in 2020, and then subtracted the two and saved the result in the variable observed_diff_in_means for later. Finally, I visualized the two groups in histograms.

It’s difficult to conclude much from these graphs. Clearly, the number of observers in both years skews heavily toward fewer than 5. It appears that there were greater amounts of bigger groups in 2019 than in 2020, which would make sense given that large birding events were likely cancelled in 2020.

My first hypothesis is that birders birded in smaller groups in 2020 during the pandemic than they did in 2019 pre-pandemic. The following are the corresponding null and alternative hypotheses:

Mb : Mean before the pandemic
Mp : Mean during the pandemic

H0 : Mb - Mp <= 0
HA : Mb - Mp > 0

In plain text, my alternative hypothesis is that the difference in means when I subtract 2020 from 2019 will be greater than 0, indicating that people birded in larger groups in 2019.

I first created a dataset containing only March & April of 2019 and 2020, and selected only a handful of columns. I ended up creating a new column, converting the year into characters, because without doing so I was getting error messages. Then, I followed the infer workflow as detailed in our textbook.

march_april_2_years <- ebird %>% dplyr::select(GLOBAL.UNIQUE.IDENTIFIER, COMMON.NAME, NUMBER.OBSERVERS, TRIP.COMMENTS, year, month) %>%
  filter(year == 2019 & month == 3 | year == 2019 & month == 4 | year == 2020 & month == 3 | year == 2020 & month == 4)

march_april_2_years <- march_april_2_years %>% 
  mutate(use_this_year = as.character(year))


head(march_april_2_years %>% 
  group_by(use_this_year) %>% 
  summarize(n = n(), mean_obs = mean(NUMBER.OBSERVERS, na.rm = T), std_dev = sd(NUMBER.OBSERVERS, na.rm = T)))
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
##   use_this_year     n mean_obs std_dev
##   <chr>         <int>    <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 2019          58517     4.49    6.51
## 2 2020          44892     2.05    3.25
null_distribution_means <- march_april_2_years %>% 
  specify(formula = NUMBER.OBSERVERS ~ use_this_year) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("2019", "2020"))

head(null_distribution_means)
## Response: NUMBER.OBSERVERS (numeric)
## Explanatory: use_this_year (factor)
## Null Hypothesis: independence
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   replicate     stat
##       <int>    <dbl>
## 1         1 -0.0305 
## 2         2 -0.00931
## 3         3 -0.0102 
## 4         4  0.00425
## 5         5  0.0198 
## 6         6 -0.0199
visualize(null_distribution_means, bins = 10)

visualize(null_distribution_means, bins = 10)+
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = observed_diff_in_means, direction = "right", color = "orange")

null_distribution_means %>% 
  get_p_value(obs_stat = observed_diff_in_means, direction = "right")
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1       0

As the second visualization shows, the null distribution is nowhere near overlapping with the observed statistic. The p-value is very close to zero, which tells me that I can reject the null hypothesis and assume that the year (i.e., whether or not it was during lockdown/pandemic) had an affect on the average size of birding groups.

I also wanted to know more specifically whether more people birded alone during the pandemic. To prepare for this test, I created a copy of the dataset containing March-April of the two years, removed NAs in the NUMBER.OBSERVERS column, and created a new column in which a group size of 1 was designated by “Single” and all other group sizes fell into the category “Group.” I decided to construct a confidence interval for this test.

If I were to write null and alternative hypotheses for this test, they would go like:

Pb : proportion of birders birding alone before the pandemic
Pp : proportion of birders birding alone during the pandemic

H0 : Pb - Pp >= 0
HA : Pb - Pp < 0

In words: The difference in proportions should be a negative number, indicating that the proportion of birders birding alone was greater in 2020 than in 2019. Year is the treatment variable, while alone_or_not is the response variable (8.6.1 of the textbook).

copy_2_years <- march_april_2_years

copy_2_years <- copy_2_years %>% filter(!is.na(NUMBER.OBSERVERS))

copy_2_years <- copy_2_years %>%
  mutate(NUMBER.OBSERVERS = if_else(NUMBER.OBSERVERS == 1, "Single", "Group")) %>%
  mutate(alone_or_not = NUMBER.OBSERVERS)

bootstrap_distribution_alone <- copy_2_years %>% 
  specify(formula = alone_or_not ~ use_this_year, success = "Single") %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("2019", "2020"))

head(bootstrap_distribution_alone)
## Response: alone_or_not (factor)
## Explanatory: use_this_year (factor)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   replicate   stat
##       <int>  <dbl>
## 1         1 -0.121
## 2         2 -0.127
## 3         3 -0.123
## 4         4 -0.125
## 5         5 -0.128
## 6         6 -0.127
alone_ci_percent <- bootstrap_distribution_alone %>% 
  get_confidence_interval(type = "percentile", level = 0.95)

alone_ci_percent
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   lower_ci upper_ci
##      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1   -0.128   -0.116
obs_diff_in_props <- copy_2_years %>% 
  specify(formula = alone_or_not ~ use_this_year, success = "Single") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("2019", "2020"))

obs_diff_in_props
## Response: alone_or_not (factor)
## Explanatory: use_this_year (factor)
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##     stat
##    <dbl>
## 1 -0.122
alone_ci_se <- bootstrap_distribution_alone %>% 
  get_confidence_interval(type = "se", point_estimate = obs_diff_in_props)

alone_ci_se
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   lower_ci upper_ci
##      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1   -0.128   -0.116
visualize(bootstrap_distribution_alone) +
  shade_confidence_interval(endpoints = alone_ci_percent, color = "orange", fill = "pink") +
   geom_vline(xintercept = -.122, color = "cornflowerblue") +
  shade_confidence_interval(endpoints = alone_ci_se, color = "pink", fill = "orange")

The textbook interprets confidence intervals as follows: “If we repeated our sampling procedure a large number of times, we expect about 95% of the resulting confidence intervals to capture the value of the population parameter” (8.5.2). In other words, every time I bootstrap my sample population and construct CIs, there is a 95% chance that the CI will contain the actual difference in proportions. In this case, as seen in the visualization, the observed difference in proportions in contained within both the percentage and the standard error CIs. Also, since the CIs do not contain 0, I have evidence suggesting that the proportion of people birding alone was indeed affected by the pandemic.

Nonetheless, the difference is very small. This makes sense to me, as I’m sure many people still went birding with partners or housemates even during lockdown. A quick perusal of the free-text TRIP.COMMENTS column in 2020 suggested as much:

“With Donna looking for butterflies”
“With Judy [last name removed], mostly cloudy, breezy, 66 F. Low tide was 6:45am”
“with Jane. Our first time exploring this beautiful area, looking forward to a return trip soon”

On March 22, 2020, a birder wrote this note in his observation:

“Leading the weekly bird walk at Magnolia. My friend Joe came along. Cool, cloudy and overcast,, (basically a gray day and very slow), with a slight occasional breeze. The property was devoid of visitors. This may be the last bird walk for a while as I have been informed. I’m not sure. To our ‘regulars’, I’ll keep you posted.”

On March 21, 2020, the governor of South Carolina ordered law enforcement to break up crowds on state beaches; on March 23, the governor ordered any gathering of three or more people to be dispersed (Greenville News, March 23, 2020). I didn’t expect to be moved by a dataset, but working with this data reminded me just how much our lives have changed since 2020 — and getting to know the birders through their comments reminded me how data can only hint at the lives of the people it contains.
